This beautiful piece will come floated in an ornate frame to highlight the deckled edges, surrounded by a mat under UV plexiglass, ready to hang and become part of your collection. ✨

Tara McPherson was born in 1976 and raised in Los Angeles. She received a BFA with honours from Art Center College of Design in California. Master of the illustrative technique she is able to blend her paint perfectly with a meticulous pictorial approach to originate otherworldly figures and a pastel palette, and use it to colour her black and pink extravagant backgrounds. In the middle of a psychedelic scene, the women’s eyes stand out wide open to freeze the viewer through the magnetism their magenta iris.
 
It is evident that McPherson’s art is all about a hypnotic relation between her seductive characters and us; those that try to stun our senses, to steal our soul and bring it around to a magic land.
 
Here everything shines to the rhythm of fireworks, or limpid water, where drops turn to diamonds, symbolism reveals in sparks of stars and little hearts that decompose as atoms to leave the figures heartless. If this should make them cold and lonely, a cosmic aura surrounds them to make all dynamic and saturated with energy.

#joymangallery #dorothycircusgallery #gallery #artgallery #art #illustration #painting #oilpainting

Tara McPherson’s first solo show ‘Lost Constellations’ in NYC broke new ground for the artist back in 2008, and gained praise across the art world. Evolution Of Language is a portrait that shows you can say a lot, without saying anything. Traveling the globe can lead you on adventures where you might not know the local dialect. Body language, using your hands and eyes, can get you a long way and maybe even better than where you were meant to be going. Mr. Wiggles, the balloon, is one of those friends who doesn’t speak but sure knows how to communicate. It’s all in those eyes and wiggles that balloons do best. Their relationship has evolved beyond traditional communication. She doesn’t even need to speak when with these friends. I hope you all know a person or two who can say it all with their eyes!
✨❤️✨

What was once my beautiful brand new art studio, got cascades of waterfalls from a burst pipe on Christmas Eve. We have quite a bit of work to do in there to get her back in safe and proper working order. We’re currently running a 15% OFF Valentine’s Day Sale at the moment, so if you have been thinking about getting a print or anything from me, now would be an amazing time to show your support and help us fundraise for my studio repairs. Also to my wonderful collectors that are waiting on commissioned paintings from me, I apologize for (yet again) more delays. Between my eternal health issues and good ol’ life curveballs, sometimes you just have to laugh hysterically at how life unfolds. Sigh. Breath. Cry. Exhale. Scream. Eat an ice cream cone. Breath. Smile. Repeat. I know life will be ok again eventually. I will get back to painting here and there, one way or another, even if in my living room! So if you are able, it would really be a super duper cool time to buy a print or some stickers from my webstore #TheCottonCandyMachine!! 
✨🙏 ✨
I also have some original oil paintings available in NYC at @wcc.art, in LA at @kpprojectsgallery and in Rome @dorothycircus. I also have some framed drawings and a very large painting series here direct from my studio…  info(at)taramcpherson.com if interested. 🎨

We decided the best solution was to partner with a company that was larger to aid us in this process. We have started with a small selection on there. If there is a specific print you are looking for that is up on The Cotton Candy Machine, but not yet on our Etsy shop, please let us know, and we will pop it up there for you! May is Ehlers Danlos Syndrome + Hypermobile Spectrum Disorder awareness month. EDS is a hereditary genetic disorder that results in weak connective tissue, which is literally everywhere in our bodies. I only got my Hypermobile EDS diagnosis 2 years ago, but it explains so much. It was such a relief to finally understand WHY my body is the way it is. Today’s prompt from @ehlers.danlos is ‘What you see, and what you don’t’, and that statement in and of itself really encapsulates EDS. It’s of course very difficult with invisible illnesses, and wanting to show a brave face. Sometimes you may see someone obviously exhausted or in pain, wearing a brace, or using an assistive device they need, but sometimes you don’t and the struggle and pain might be there just the same. It’s always good to remind ourselves often, myself included, that we just don’t know what someone else is going through. We just can’t see it all on the surface. I know I am so thankful to those who are compassionate to me, especially random people that I don’t even know. It’s such a wonderful quality of being a good human. I hope I can give that to others every day. ❤️ 
Photo by @allanamato + @olga_nunes
✨
#eds #hEDS #hsd #myedshallenge #hypermobileehlersdanlos #edsstrong

Going in today for a big procedure on my neck to help with lingering nerve pain. I had two separate trial tests with lidocaine in March, and a few weeks ago had the 1st round of cervical medial branch nerve ablation on my left side, where they cauterize the nerves as they come out of the facet joints. I had a positive response fortunately and it cut down my occipital neuralgia by like 85%!!So today we are doing the right side of my neck. I’ll be back in action next week ❤️ 
UPDATE! : I’m home and resting, coming out of the sedation haze,  waiting for my pain meds to work, because dang, it’s super ouchie! My pain management doctor is so great, and also funny… he said doing my procedure with the fluoroscopy (live x-ray guidance) is like the final boss level of a video game because of all my titanium hardware 😂
✨💪🏼✨
#myEDSchallenge #occipitalneuralgia #hEDS #nerveablation

Today’s prompt from @ehlers.danlos is to shine a light on a type of EDS. The one I have, and the most common, is Hypermobile Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome or hEDS for short. I had symptoms of weak connective tissue my whole life, but thought I was just really flexible. I was always clumsy… spraining my wrists, fingers, and ankles constantly, not knowing this was a sign of loose ligaments and unstable joints. When I would carry heavy bags, if I relaxed my muscles, I could feel my arms pulling out of the shoulder joint. I just thought this was normal! I also developed scoliosis. I noticed my scars would heal weird & look like crinkly paper, or would heal into a little crater. When I was 13 I was diagnosed with Chiari Malformation & Syringomyelia. I had emergency brain surgery to allow room for my spinal fluid to flow. Surprise, Chiari is common with EDS! As I got older I was always exhausted, I would push myself very hard but then I would have to rest hard too. I never had the same stamina as others, even though I was very driven. I’m so glad I did so much in my career before I started a family, because after I had children my symptoms definitely got worse. I started having major flares with Craniocervical Instability (CCI) ultimately culminating in having my neck permanently fused from Occiput-T2, w/ ACDF C4-C7, to stabilize my spine. It was hard to process, but by getting diagnosed with hEDS by my geneticist, I learned all about it and all the crazy things my body was going through. I’ve gotten to a better place now and many of my symptoms are controlled by meds, supplements, diet, bracing, and exercise. Though I don’t know what my future holds, I have the KNOWLEDGE now, and that makes all the difference. I’m working on my mental health and in a better state of mind, and that’s what it boils down to right?! A positive state of mind. Because life is hard for literally everyone. We ALL have health issues, mental struggles & trauma, but it’s how we frame it, gain knowledge, and get the right help, that makes all the difference. ❤️
Pic by @debbie.bean 
✨
#myedschallenge

Flare, my least favorite word, but one used a lot nowadays. Today’s prompt from @ehlers.danlos is ‘Warning Signs of a Symptom Flare’. I used to call it an ‘acute attack’ when my neck would pinch & I’d be unable to move my neck for a few days. I had emergency meds to help, but it would happen out of the blue… opening a drawer, slipping on wet grass. Then after having kids, my flares grew to include my right arm and hand being debilitated for months at a time simply from looking down instead of upright on my easel, signing artbooks, or painting a mural. Steroid injections helped avoid the inevitable, until I desperately needed the dreaded 2nd spinal surgery. After surgery, my flares grew to include strange allergic reactions, nausea, GI issues, muscle spasms, fatigue, vertigo & a constant rotating array of painful joints. It’s a strange world folks! Not one I imagined myself in, that’s for sure, but one that I’m fortunate to know A LOT about now. One thing I’m very grateful for are the FB Health Groups that I joined, informative websites, and the research papers out there. I listened to other’s experiences, and by reading and learning I slowly pieced together the puzzle of my health issues, along with my doctors, primarily by advocating for myself and asking the right questions. I’ll be honest, I have joked that my health is my part time job these past few years, and the truth is it is! It takes SO much time for doctors appointments, physical therapy, testing, bloodwork, imaging & all the other diagnostics that docs need to figure out what the heck our bodies are up to! I’m finally slowly emerging into a good place. I still flare from overdoing it, also randomly, but now I have a better handle on what to do! Grab the right brace, sleep good, rest, heat, ice, increase my exercises, go to PT, vestibular rehab, & taking the right meds. Flaring is just simply a part of life for many of us, and life must go on, especially for important things! I try my best to mitigate it, & with laughter, love, patience, & a good serotonin level I can deal with it better. But when it happens… ya’ just gotta roll with the punches as best you can!
✨
#myedschallenge #spoonie #flareup

IT’S MY 3 YEAR SPINE-IVERSARY!! 3 very, very long years since my spinal fusion surgery that changed my life. Occiput to T2 posterior fusion and ACDF C4-C7. I can finally say I am in a place where I think I have reached my new baseline. I kind of know my limits, what I’m capable of, and what I should avoid doing. It’s been of course one of the most painful and challenging things I have ever gone through in my life, and I’m still figuring it out. After my fusion surgery in 2020 my system went totally downhill from the trauma, and so many secondary health issues common with #EhlersDanlosSyndrome creeped up like #Gastroparesis, #MastCellActivation, bad #LigamentPain, 3 kinds of #Vertigo, and #AutonomicSmallFiberNeuropathy, plus I developed #UlcerativeColitis for the first time, and it all really complicated my recovery. After the physical healing which I focused on so heavily these past 3 years, my mental health suffered. Well, to be honest, IS suffering. I am in the thick of some severe depression, anxiety, and other issues, and am trying to work on my head right now. Maybe it’s a mid life crisis? PTSD? Maybe I need a reboot? Maybe I need a big change? Maybe… I just don’t know what I need? I’m pretty lost. But I’m hanging in there. I’m talking to a therapist every week, and trying to learn and re-learn how to be a person again. But it’s hard. Life is super overwhelming. Apologies to anyone waiting on anything from me. I just don’t have much to give right now. Trying to figure out my new life and what priorities are the most important, while trying to be a good mom, wife, and friend, AND trying to survive financially and have an income, while I am trying to heal and be kind and gentle to myself is very difficult. I don’t have answers. I have lots of questions. I just wanted to share some honesty in my struggles, because social media is so full of itself sometimes with these false notions of life and inspiration. And sometimes life just isn’t very inspiring, it’s just hard. I hope you all hang in there with me too.

Hey there, these totally cool and not cumbersome at all braces are my new frens. 
For the past couple months my arms have been getting progressively worse with #TennisElbow (and dang it I don’t even have any cool tennis moves to show for it!) My guess is gardening and working, so laaaaaame! Watering the garden is like my new mental health morning routine, and obvs working is super essential… I’m so bummed! 
So today I got bilateral injections in my elbow tendons to ramp up the healing process. Ain’t got time for this nonsense! I’ll be wearing these sexy wristies for a little while. They basically prevent my hands from flexion and extension, giving my arm muscles/tendons a chance to rest and heal the tears. I don’t think my body cared for the regular tennis elbow braces much, as they were flaring up my #cubitaltunnel and some other stuff. Thank goodness for the #accessibilityfeatures on my computer so I can dictate my emails and simply tell my computer what I want it to do. Highly recommend if your arms or neck are suffering!
✨
Anyone else go through this business? Any assistive gardening hacks? What tips tricks helped you heal? What made it worse? I start PT shortly (after I finish up my knee PT 😂), have been icing + heating, blue rub, got puffy padded armrests for my studio chair, 1:1 tincture, stretching, and resting. Also I maybe might be moving like a T. Rex to protect my arms…🦖 Thanks! 🙏

October is Dysautonomia awareness month, and while I am still in the middle of my diagnosis, I have been struggling with symptoms my whole life. “Dysautonomia” is the general term for disorders that disrupt your autonomic nervous system (ANS). Dizziness (especially when standing up), balance problems, brain fog, fatigue, shortness of breath, heat and cold intolerance, sound or light sensitivity, sweat dysfunction (either more, or less, than normal), nausea, heart palpitations, and many other symptoms. I first heard about #Dysautonomia a few years ago when I was learning about having hypermobile Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, and all the symptoms made complete sense for me. I finally got in for autonomic testing last year and I was positive for autonomic small fiber neuropathy, but oddly enough not on my blood pressure testing, even though I’m symptomatic. I found a new autonomic neurologist who specializes in dysautonomia, and I’m going in for more testing next month since they do suspect that I have some form of orthostatic intolerance… which basically means that I have an intolerance for standing up sometimes lol, we just need to figure out what it is exactly. Everyone’s symptoms vary greatly, but mine include feeling faint when standing up, weak when upright, super lethargic in the heat or shower, huge intolerance for the cold, cold hands, thumbs go numb when I get too cold, extremely dry skin and lack of sweating, pins and needles in my arms and legs, feeling like I don’t breathe deep enough, or I forget to breathe when I’m concentrating, sensitivity to light, very slow digestion which results in nausea and other fun issues, and just generally feeling like I’m getting sick when I’m not sick. Honestly, today is one of those days! I woke up and I just didn’t feel right at all, and it was just simply hard to stand up! I wanted to write this to you all before October finished, to help raise awareness for this super weird disabling condition that I struggle with. PS- Yes, my arms/wrists/thumbs are still all jacked up with tendinitis! Find more info on @dysautonomiaintl

I’m having another vertigo flare that started on Friday night. I’m starting to lose count now because it keeps happening, but I think this is the 6th time?! For me when I have vertigo, I feel like I’m on a boat wearing roller skates. I just kind of feel like I’m sliding around through life. It’s a really weird feeling that intensifies when I am moving around, and gets better when I am still. The doctors say I experience 3 kinds of vertigo… Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV), Vestibulo-Ocular Reflex asymmetry, and Cervicogenic Vertigo. But the weirdest part about vertigo is when I lay down or roll over in bed and I get the really severe spinning sensations I get something called nystagmus in my eyes, which is what I wanted to show you here in the video. Nystagmus is the rapid and uncontrolled movement of both eyes, typically in a fast or slow rhythmic pattern. It lasts maybe like 30 seconds before it fades. We’re still trying to figure out why I repeatedly keep getting vertigo, but my vestibular therapist had warned me that since I’ve had it happened so often, it’s likely to just continue to recur throughout my life. Hopefully I’ll discover why and be able to prevent it from happening so often. But for now I’m waiting for my appointment for the amazing therapists to do the Epley maneuver on me. Because my spine is now fused, and I can’t really do it on my own, they’ve come up with a very creative way to get my ear crystals back in place! I think when I go in I will have them film the maneuver so I can try to fix it from home in the future, because waiting 10 days for an appointment feels like forever! I do have meds I’m taking in the meantime. Anyone else get nystagmus with vertigo?

Today, 19 years ago, we took our very first order.
By accident.
We were trying to put our shop together and get our suppliers to take us seriously when a local small business owner walked in and asked if we could frame a couple of things for him.
😬👀😁👀😬
Ok, let’s go!!!
•
That’s it. 
We opened. 
It was so much fun decorating that store. We wallpapered the back wall with pages from Lewis Carroll’s “Alice in Wonderland”, spray painted and decorated vintage chandeliers to look like toleware, stapled tuff turf to the wall and built tables strong enough to hold a school bus. 

Still true today we are trucking thru🤞and doing our best to adapt while maintaining our high standards of a quality custom frame paired with exceptional customer service and respect.

We have one location with three employees where all work is done on-site and most likely by the person who took your order.
 
Come by and frame stuff with us so we can be around for 20+ more years.

Our framing has no limitations and guarantee’s a truly custom experience.

We are thankful and love you all.
